I tried all of the \"feed additives\" and none of them worked for my dog, but I've had clients that they have worked for so I would give that a shot. Also, try switching dogs foods too. My dog would only eat the poop of my roommates dog and when we changed that dogs diet from fish based to chicken based she stopped. The most important thing is to keep him from doing it as often as possible by picking up poop from the yard immediately. Each time he eats some he is rewarding his own behavior and learning to do it more. For my dog, negative reinforcement worked (telling her no when she got close to eating or started smelling poop, or blowing an air horn when she smelled it) but I have heard for some dogs it can actually make the behavior worse...I guess it depends on how your dog handles discipline. Also, teaching you're dog the \"leave it\" command can be very helpful. My dog has mostly stopped the behavior with some discipline, but she still loves cat poop, rabbit poop, ferret poop, or any dog poop from a dog that eats a fish based diet. It's disgusting. The best advice I have is to keep breath-freshening chews or snacks handy and to never let him lick you're face without smelling his breath first lol. However, once the coronavirus is in the macrophage the macrophage can't clear it and the virus replicates and spreads more virus. Vaccination can make the disease worse if it programs the body to  produce more Ab upon exposure and thus allow more viral replication in the macrophages. {"from": {"id": "1531830359", "name": "Juli Tisdale"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/186721998039954/posts/379707972074688", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2012-04-15T22:40:29+0000", "to": {"data": [{"name": "Texas A&M College of Veterinary Medicine Class of 2015", "id": "186721998039954"}]}, "comments": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "MzgxNTMzMjQxODkyMTYx", "before": "Mzc5NzI0NTM4NzM5Njk4"}}, "data": [{"from": {"id": "1544160181", "name": "Toni Yang"}, "like_count": 2, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-04-13T22:13:16+0000", "message": "basically he's saying that a mutation fron ncpBVDV to cpBVDV WITHIN one cow will result in disease for that animal b/c the cow's immune system will ID it as self-antigen and won't attack it even though it's cp now.  this is also the case for other cows in the same herd that have the same original ncpBVDV and are infected by the mutated virus. <-- both of these situations are homologous challenges.\n\nhowever if cpBVDV from ANOTHER source [ie another herd] infects a ncpBVDV infected cow, there WILL be an immune response because it's a completely different virus. <-- this is a case of heterogenous challenge\n\nand the slides with the baby are just saying that persistently infected cows will always produce persistently infected calves so it's important to cull the PI cows\n\nlol sry it's a bit long but hope that helps c:", "id": "379724538739698", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1531500092", "name": "Cassi Seibold"}, "like_count": 7, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-04-13T22:52:39+0000", "message": "Magic", "id": "379744655404353", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1531830359", "name": "Juli Tisdale"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-04-13T23:34:10+0000", "message": "thank you so much! An increased P50 indicates a rightward shift of the curve because a larger partial pressure is necessary to maintain 50% oxygen saturation. This indicates a decreased affinity.  Conversely, a lower P50 indicates a leftward shift and a higher affinity.", "id": "348445885200897", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1547970273", "name": "Suzanne Li"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-02-27T06:21:52+0000", "message": "Then yep that's right.", "id": "348446631867489", "user_likes": false}]}, "created_time": "2012-02-27T05:50:14+0000", "message": "Correct me if I'm wrong on this please :)  Thanks!\n\nOxygen-Hemoglobin Dissociation Curve\n\nLEFT SHIFTERS: Promotes LOADING of O2 and is associated with an increase in Oxygen Affinity, Carbon Monoxide, Increase in PCO2, Decrease in PO2 (hypoxia), FETAL Hb, Decrease in 2,3-DPG, Increase in pH (alkalosis), high altitude, Decrease in Temperature, Hyperventilation, Carboxyhemoglobin, Right to Left Cardiac Shunt, Decrease in p50\n\nRIGHT SHIFTERS: Promotes UNLOADING of O2 and is associated with a decrease in Oxygen Affinity, TISSUES NEED MORE OXYGEN!!!, exercise/starvation, Increase in pCO2, Increase in PO2, Increase in 2,3-DPG, Febrile State (Increase Temp), Sickle Cell Anemia, Decrease in pH (acidosis), ADULT Hb, Hypoventilation, Increase in p50", "type": "status", "id": "186721998039954_348437175201768"}

{"from": {"id": "1311273368", "name": "Karen Reyff Abichandani"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/186721998039954/posts/311010542277765", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2012-01-07T15:28:28+0000", "to": {"data": [{"name": "Texas A&M College of Veterinary Medicine Class of 2015", "id": "186721998039954"}]}, "likes": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "NjE0NzUzMDYw", "before": "NjY5Njg1MjEx"}}, "data": [{"id": "669685211", "name": "Claire Elizabeth Gibson"}, {"id": "603983722", "name": "Laura Ron"}, {"id": "8344149", "name": "Natalie Thompson"}, {"id": "614753060", "name": "Britni Burns"}]}, "created_time": "2012-01-07T03:12:58+0000", "message": "Hello! I thought it would be a good idea to tell you guys my \"lessons learned\" from this past semester while they are fresh in my mind. I know you don't care about it right now, but come back and read this when you're about to start second year. :) Also, this is my opinion and I'm sure some of my classmates will feel differently.\n\nAssuming your fall semester classes are basically the same as our fall semester classes:\nPharmacology - print out the study guides created by someone in 2013 and use them to take notes. You don't get actual notes with specifics about the drugs you need to learn so those study guides helped me a lot. The reading guides, which are what you buy for the class, helped me for the first test, but once you get to drugs, there's a lot of material to read through and the professors don't do the best job letting you know what they care about. Remind me to send the study guides to you. Also, the syllabus says each lecture is worth about 8 points of questions on each test. This suggested to us that most of the final would be over antibiotics and the rest of the material could be kind of glanced at. THIS IS NOT TRUE. Study everything for the final.\n\nPathology - I liked this class a lot and I don't have much to say here except don't forget to review the powerpoints from the labs before each test. Oh, and there are a couple professors I don't want to name (but you will totally know who they are) who aren't very good lecturers. I went to class anyway during those sections because that's just how I am, but some people skipped those lectures and just studied the notes.\n\nParasitology - study your hiney off for the first test. You will probably need a solid A on it to cushion you from the pain of the midterm and third test. Happily, I thought the final exam was pretty easy relative to how the midterm was, but I might have just finally figured out how to study for it. Don't slack off for the final! Oh, and people told us that Dr. Craig tries to fail a bunch of people every year and is forced to curve. That's probably a wishful rumor because my grade tells me there was either no curve for our class or it was a tiny bump. Either way, my grade didn't change. Study your butt off for this class!\n\nNutrition - don't wait to review the material for this class until right before each test. It's really easy to push this class to the background, but you'll save yourself some trouble if you review everything a week or so before your tests and again right before each test. As long as you don't let the information pile up until last minute, the tests aren't too bad in this class.\n\nClinical Correlates - I hope they change this class for you guys. We were supposed to go out and actually interact with live animals as part of this class, but it never happened. Mostly the class consisted of lectures over various topics and case reviews. There weren't any tests and I'm pretty sure everyone automatically got an A so that's nice.\n\nOverall first semester of second year was a lot of lecture and zero live animal interaction through class. You have more free time than first year so look forward to that!", "type": "status", "id": "186721998039954_311010542277765", "comments": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "MzExMjg1MDAyMjUwMzE5", "before": "MzExMDQ1OTg4OTQwODg3"}}, "data": [{"from": {"id": "1091801108", "name": "Kevin Burch"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-01-07T04:39:55+0000", "message": "Thank you for the info!", "id": "311045988940887", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1311273368", "name": "Karen Reyff Abichandani"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2012-01-07T15:28:28+0000", "message": "You're welcome :)", "id": "311285002250319", "user_likes": false}]}}

{"from": {"id": "8380865", "name": "Roy Moore"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/186721998039954/posts/267127679999385", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2011-10-23T03:46:41+0000", "to": {"data": [{"name": "Texas A&M College of Veterinary Medicine Class of 2015", "id": "186721998039954"}]}, "comments": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "MjY3MTgwMTI2NjYwODA3", "before": "MjY3MTI5MjY5OTk5MjI2"}}, "data": [{"from": {"id": "735025884", "name": "Erin Binagia"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-23T00:46:29+0000", "message": "its the relationship between wall stress, pressure, radius, and wall thickness of the heart; if the heart radius increases (like in a failing heart) wall stress will increase (large radius makes it harder to generate pressure, remember Frank-Starling) The heart will increase its wall thickness in order to decrease the radius so that it can generate the same pressure easier. This will allow the heart to be more effective in generating pressure. the trade-off is that decreasing the radius will decrease the stroke volume (due to decreased EDV). This is an adaptive change over time.. Hope that helps", "id": "267129269999226", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "8380865", "name": "Roy Moore"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-23T02:05:44+0000", "message": "Thank you.  I appreciate it!", "id": "267152183330268", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "8380865", "name": "Roy Moore"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-23T02:08:37+0000", "message": "The radius will increase because of hypertrophy of the heart, correct?", "id": "267153009996852", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "735025884", "name": "Erin Binagia"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-23T03:46:41+0000", "message": "no, the radius would increase if the ventricles were volume-loaded like in a failing heart.. hypertrophy would increase the wall thickness and therefore decrease the radius", "id": "267180126660807", "user_likes": false}]}, "created_time": "2011-10-23T00:40:37+0000", "message": "Hey does any one understand the Law of LaPlace? {"from": {"id": "38601511", "name": "Stephanie Russell Beeson"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/186721998039954/posts/257507257628094", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2011-10-02T14:11:24+0000", "to": {"data": [{"name": "Texas A&M College of Veterinary Medicine Class of 2015", "id": "186721998039954"}]}, "comments": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "MjU3NzUxODAwOTM2OTcz", "before": "MjU3NTA5ODcwOTYxMTY2"}}, "data": [{"from": {"id": "1529400079", "name": "Lindsey Mathews"}, "like_count": 3, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-01T22:25:49+0000", "message": "Isotonic is a constant tension and changing lengths. This includes body movements such as lifting something or lowering something to the ground. Isometric is the opposite - constant length but changing tension, so you're not actively moving your muscles. He gave the example of pushing against a wall in class - you're still doing work, but your muscles aren't changing in length. Another example is posture, you're in a fixed position, but your muscles are still working. Another example is if you're holding something still. So you could be going from Isometric contractions by lifting a weight up (concentric), then if you are holding it in your hands in the same position, its isometric...then if you lower it back down, you go back to isotonic (eccentric). Hope that helps...I don't think we have to go super in depth for it.", "id": "257509870961166", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "647081457", "name": "Stephanie Parker Probandt"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-01T22:29:32+0000", "message": "Thanks Lindsey!", "id": "257510860961067", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "38601511", "name": "Stephanie Russell Beeson"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-02T14:11:24+0000", "message": "Thanks! As I thought about the question, I came close to telling them that I was in the process of slowly losing my sanity and social life. We are lucky. So when you feel like you're about to go crazy because of the huge demands and workloads, just remember: we are in this for a reason, this is our career; our dream! As in, are we expected to be wearing business casual every day, like they say we need to for vet school itself?", "id": "201547366557417", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1311273368", "name": "Karen Reyff Abichandani"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-05-23T11:03:21+0000", "message": "Yes, officially it's the same dress code. That said, \"business casual\" or \"professional dress\" doesn't mean what it would mean if you were working for a corporation in Dallas. For example, Dr. Hoffman often wears jeans, a short-sleeved button down shirt, and a tie. In a corporate setting, jeans aren't business casual or professional dress so the description was confusing to me. A lot of people in my workshop wore nice jeans, boots (must be close-toed shoes) and a polo or button down shirt. Some wore dressier clothes like slacks. None of the guys wore a tie in the workshop, but we do have one classmate who wears a suit and tie every day to class during the semester. You can change into scrubs before the lab if you want, but you shouldn't wear them to the lecture part of the class unless Dr. Frank (or whoever is teaching it this summer) tells you that's OK.", "id": "201603553218465", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "603983722", "name": "Laura Ron"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-05-23T14:30:57+0000", "message": "Okay, awesome, that's exactly what I needed to know - thanks, Karen!  :-)", "id": "201647013214119", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1010132514", "name": "Samantha Rosenbaum"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-05-23T15:21:04+0000", "message": "Thanks!", "id": "201657399879747", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "1010132514", "name": "Samantha Rosenbaum"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-05-26T20:25:42+0000", "message": "Did anyone get the email regarding supplies yet?", "id": "202465106465643", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "715100156", "name": "Stephanie Malmquist"}, "like_count": 1, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-05-31T15:50:25+0000", "message": "Hey everyone! Don't spend a ton of money on new clothing unless you don't own a single pair of nice jeans, a shirt that is not a t-shirt or a tank top, and closed-toe shoes. For orientation, it's probably a good idea to wear slacks and a nice shirt and shoes, but seriously don't buy a bunch of new clothing until you see what other classes wear unless you are looking for a reason to go shopping. You can't wear tank tops, shorts or pajamas. You can't wear open-toed shoes (flip flops) in lab. Scrubs are controversial. Some professors do not like them and do not want you to wear them unless you are in the lab (remember there are locker rooms where you can change), but there are people who wear them every day anyway.
